en_119504_0	Turkey's ruling Justice and Development Party (AKP) has won a critical parliamentary election, regaining the majority it lost in June.
en_119504_1	With almost all ballots counted, state-run Anadolu Agency said AKP had won 49.4% of the vote, with the main opposition CHP on 25.4%.
en_119504_2	President Recep Tayyip Erdogan said voters had "shown that they prefer action and development to controversy".
en_119504_3	The pro-Kurdish HDP crossed the 10% threshold needed to claim seats.
en_119504_4	The nationalist MHP will also take seats in Ankara.
en_119504_5	In a statement, Mr Erdogan said the electorate had "given proof of their strong desire for the unity and integrity" of Turkey.
